Beowulf was supposed to be partly real, partly cartoonish. Actually, I don't even know what the hell they were trying for with the animation in Beowulf. Zemeckis has been going downhill since Cast Away and that sucks.

Tin Tin is being made as a live-action cartoon, literally. It's a great, compelling story that could easily be done with obvious real life actors. But, this kind of animation kind of gives it a new spin, which is kind of cool, IMO.

@MartySynyster
Did you notice the Bird Bros had the EXACT same expression in every panel? No expression, no emotion, no sense of class even. Just a couple of crooks who stumbled on to something and thought "Goody, money."
The way Sakharine was portrayed in the movie was great. He had spirit, a plan, legacy/motive, and a cruel streak. Just much more cooler and fun overall. How he was portrayed in the comics makes zilch difference. This isn't the comic, it's the movie.

@Janus781204
You need to remember that this has all been adapted to suit the audience of a different medium, including an audience not entirely familiar with Tintin. The film has to appeal to everyone and some changes were made for the better.
I personally loved it. Great plot, excellent morals and some crafty references for die-hard book fans, it was great both visually and emotionally. Really, what was wrong with it?

